# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: grounding-shielding
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:grounding-shielding/chassis-ground] A **chassis ground** is a link between different metallic parts of a machine to ensure an electrical connection between them.
[src:grounding-shielding/chassis-ground] Examples include electronic instruments and motor vehicles.
[src:grounding-shielding/chassis-ground] Most electronic systems have their circuits reference-linked to the chassis while the chassis itself is often, but not always, linked to the Earth.
[src:grounding-shielding/chassis-ground] Most motor vehicles use the chassis as the reference for all electrical peripherals which allow the use of only one wire for each accessory.
[src:grounding-shielding/chassis-ground] The chassis must not be considered as a link to Earth.
[src:grounding-shielding/chassis-ground] Depending on the usage of electrical machines, this may or may not be the case.
[src:grounding-shielding/chassis-ground] For example, in all cars metallic parts are linked together but they are not linked to the Earth.
[src:grounding-shielding/chassis-ground] This explains why one can experience electrical discharge when leaving a car.
[src:grounding-shielding/faraday-cage] A **Faraday cage** or **Faraday shield** is an enclosure used to block some electromagnetic fields.
[src:grounding-shielding/faraday-cage] A Faraday shield may be formed by a continuous covering of conductive material, or in the case of a Faraday cage, by a mesh of such materials.
[src:grounding-shielding/faraday-cage] Faraday cages are named after the scientist Michael Faraday, who first constructed one in 1836.
[src:grounding-shielding/faraday-cage] Faraday cages work because an external electrical field will cause the electric charges within the cage's conducting material to be distributed in a way that cancels out the field's effect inside the cage.
[src:grounding-shielding/faraday-cage] This phenomenon can be used to protect sensitive electronic equipment (for example RF receivers) from external radio frequency interference (RFI), often during testing or alignment of the device.
[src:grounding-shielding/faraday-cage] Faraday cages are also used to protect people and equipment against electric currents such as lightning strikes and electrostatic discharges, because the cage conducts electrical current around the outside of the enclosed space and none passes through the interior.
[src:grounding-shielding/faraday-cage] Faraday cages cannot block stable or slowly varying magnetic fields, such as the Earth's magnetic field (a compass will still work inside one).
[src:grounding-shielding/faraday-cage] To a large degree, however, they shield the interior from external electromagnetic radiation if the conductor is thick enough and any hole is significantly smaller than the wavelength of the radiation.
[src:grounding-shielding/faraday-cage] For example, certain computer forensic electronic systems test procedures that require an electromagnetic interference free environment can be carried out within a screened room.
[src:grounding-shielding/faraday-cage] These rooms are spaces that are completely enclosed by one or more layers of a fine metal mesh or perforated sheet metal.
[src:grounding-shielding/faraday-cage] The metal layers are grounded to dissipate any electric currents generated from external or internal electromagnetic fields, and thus they block a large amount of the electromagnetic interference (see also electromagnetic shielding).
[src:grounding-shielding/faraday-cage] Near-field, high-powered frequency transmissions like HF RFID are more likely to penetrate.
[src:grounding-shielding/faraday-cage] Solid cages generally attenuate fields over a broader frequency range than mesh cages.
[src:grounding-shielding/faraday-cage] In 1754, Jean-Antoine Nollet published an account of the cage effect in his *Leçons de physique expérimentale*.
[src:grounding-shielding/faraday-cage] In 1755, Benjamin Franklin observed the effect by lowering an uncharged cork ball suspended on a silk thread through an opening in an electrically charged metal can.
[src:grounding-shielding/faraday-cage] The behavior is that of a Faraday cage or shield.
[src:grounding-shielding/faraday-cage] In 1836, Michael Faraday observed that the excess charge on a charged conductor resided only on its exterior and had no influence on anything enclosed within it.
[src:grounding-shielding/faraday-cage] To demonstrate this, he built a metal foil-coated room and allowed high-voltage discharges from an electrostatic generator to strike the outside of the room.
[src:grounding-shielding/faraday-cage] He used an electroscope to show that there was no electric charge present on the inside of the room walls.
[src:grounding-shielding/faraday-cage] A continuous Faraday shield is a hollow conductor.
[src:grounding-shielding/faraday-cage] Externally or internally applied electromagnetic fields produce forces on the charge carriers (usually electrons) within the conductor; the charges are redistributed accordingly due to electrostatic induction.
[src:grounding-shielding/faraday-cage] The redistributed charges greatly reduce the voltage within the surface, to an extent depending on the capacitance; however, full cancellation does not occur.
[src:grounding-shielding/faraday-cage] If charge $+Q$ is placed inside an ungrounded Faraday shield without touching the walls, the internal face of the shield becomes charged with $-Q$ , leading to field lines originating at the charge and extending to charges inside the inner surface of the metal.
[src:grounding-shielding/faraday-cage] The field line paths in this inside space (to the endpoint negative charges) are dependent on the shape of the inner containment walls.
[src:grounding-shielding/faraday-cage] Simultaneously $+Q$ accumulates on the outer face of the shield.
[src:grounding-shielding/faraday-cage] The spread of charges on the outer face is not affected by the position of the internal charge inside the enclosure, but rather determined by the shape of the outer face.
[src:grounding-shielding/faraday-cage] So for all intents and purposes, the Faraday shield generates the same static electric field on the outside that it would generate if the metal were simply charged with $+Q$ .
[src:grounding-shielding/faraday-cage] See Faraday's ice pail experiment, for example, for more details on electric field lines and the decoupling of the outside from the inside.
[src:grounding-shielding/faraday-cage] Note that electromagnetic waves are not static charges.
[src:grounding-shielding/faraday-cage] If the cage is grounded, the excess charges will be neutralized as the ground connection creates an equipotential bonding between the outside of the cage and the environment, so there is no voltage between them and therefore also no field.
[src:grounding-shielding/faraday-cage] The inner face and the inner charge will remain the same, so the field is kept inside.
[src:grounding-shielding/faraday-cage] Static electric shielding effectiveness is largely independent of the geometry of the conductive material; however, the static magnetic fields can penetrate the shield completely.
[src:grounding-shielding/faraday-cage] In the case of varying electromagnetic fields, the faster the variations are (i.e., the higher the frequencies), the better the material resists magnetic field penetration.
[src:grounding-shielding/faraday-cage] In this case, the shielding also depends on the electrical conductivity, the magnetic properties of the conductive materials used in the cages, as well as their thicknesses.
[src:grounding-shielding/faraday-cage] A good example of the effectiveness of a Faraday shield can be obtained from considerations of skin depth.
[src:grounding-shielding/faraday-cage] With skin depth, the current flowing is mostly on the surface and decays exponentially with depth through the material.
[src:grounding-shielding/faraday-cage] Because a Faraday shield has finite thickness, this determines how well the shield works; a thicker shield can attenuate electromagnetic fields better, and to a lower frequency.
[src:grounding-shielding/faraday-cage] Faraday cages are Faraday shields that have holes in them and are therefore more complex to analyze.
[src:grounding-shielding/faraday-cage] The shorter the wavelength, the better it passes through a mesh of a given size.
[src:grounding-shielding/faraday-cage] Thus, to work well at short wavelengths (i.e., high frequencies), the holes in the cage must be smaller than the wavelength of the incident wave.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] **Ground current** or **earth current** is the current that flows through a reference ground, earth ground, or common ground.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] To **ground** or to **earth** an object is to electrically connect the object to a reference ground, earth ground, or common ground.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Electrical circuits may be grounded for several reasons.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] A **protective earth conductor** (**PE conductor**) is a conductor that is used for electrical bonding, that is, connecting an electrical equipment from its exposed and conductive but normally unenergized part to common ground.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] If the conductor is a wire, it is also called **ground** **wire** or **earth** **wire**.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Ground wire is often used for lower voltage systems and is often colored green, or green and yellow, per standard.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Electrical bonding can protect users from electrical shock hazards.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] If internal insulation fails and the equipment is turned on, the exposed conductive parts may have dangerous voltages.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Connection of exposed conductive parts to a PE conductor provides a low-impedance path for current to flow back to the incoming neutral.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] This results in a fault and allows circuit breakers (or RCDs) to interrupt power supply.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] The current that flows through the low-impedance path is high and will usually trip the breaker or melt the safety fuse if any.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Even if the circuit does not break due to failures, the current still only flows mainly through the PE conductor instead of the user upon touching the exposed conductive part.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] A PE conductor is an essential part of the safety provided by the earthing system.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] A **safety ground** is a loose term that refers to a common ground that is used for safety purposes.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Connection to earth ground limits the build-up of static electricity.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] This connection is crucial for safety when handling flammable products or electrostatic-sensitive devices.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] In a large-scale electrical system, a piece of conducting material, called **grounding electrode** or **earthing electrode**, is buried in the soil to act as an earth ground.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] A **grounding electrode conductor** or **ground conductor** is a conductor that connects an electrical equipment to the grounding electrode.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] In some telegraph and power transmission circuits, the physical ground (an earth ground) itself can be used as one conductor of the circuit, saving the cost of installing a separate return conductor (see single-wire earth return and earth-return telegraph).
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] In an electric power system, the neutral is connected to earth ground, close to the point of entry.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] For measurement purposes, the ground of the Earth, having a reasonably constant potential, serves as a reference ground against which other potentials can be measured.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] An electrical ground system should have an appropriate current-carrying capability to serve as an adequate zero-voltage reference level.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Circuits in portable electronic devices, such as cell phones and media players, as well as circuits in vehicles, have a reference ground (also called chassis ground in those cases).
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] In electronic circuit theory, a **signal ground** is the common ground and reference ground for electric signal; and a **power ground** is the common ground for power current.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] The signal ground and power ground may be connected.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] There is usually a large conductor attached to one side of the power supply (such as the "ground plane" on a printed circuit board), which serves as the common ground, the common return path for current from many different components in the circuit.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] The signal ground and power ground are usually assumed to be an earth ground and idealized as an infinite source or sink for charge, which can absorb an unlimited amount of current without changing its potential.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Where a physical ground connection has a significant resistance, the approximation of zero potential is no longer valid (no longer a valid reference ground).
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Stray voltages or earth potential rise effects will occur, which may create noise in signals or produce an electric shock hazard if large enough.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Electrical power distribution systems are often connected to earth ground to limit the voltage that can appear on distribution circuits.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] A distribution system insulated from earth ground may attain a high potential due to transient voltages caused by static electricity or accidental contact with higher potential circuits.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] An earth ground connection of the system dissipates such potentials and limits the rise in voltage of the grounded system.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] A **grounding electrode conductor** (GEC) is used to connect the system grounded ("neutral") conductor, or the equipment to a grounding electrode, or a point on the grounding electrode system.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] This is called "system grounding" and most electrical systems are required to be grounded.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] The US NEC and the UK's BS 7671 list systems that are required to be grounded.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] According to the NEC, the purpose of connecting an electrical system to the physical ground is to limit the voltage imposed by lightning events and contact with higher voltage lines.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] In the past, water supply pipes were used as grounding electrodes, but due to the increased use of plastic pipes, which are poor conductors, the use of a specific grounding electrode is often mandated by regulating authorities.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] The same type of ground applies to radio antennas and to lightning protection systems.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Permanently installed electrical equipment, unless not required to, has permanently connected grounding conductors.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Portable electrical devices with metal cases may have them connected to earth ground by a pin on the attachment plug (see AC power plugs and sockets).
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] The size of power grounding conductors is usually regulated by local or national wiring regulations.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Bonding is the practice of intentionally electrically connecting metallic items not designed to carry electricity.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] This brings all the bonded items to the same electrical potential as a protection from electrical shock.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] The bonded items can then be connected to ground to eliminate foreign voltages.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] In electricity supply systems, an *earthing system* or *grounding system* defines the electrical potential of the conductors relative to that of the Earth's conductive surface.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] The choice of earthing system has implications for the safety and electromagnetic compatibility of the power supply.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Regulations for earthing systems vary considerably between different countries.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] A functional earth connection serves more than protecting against electrical shock, as such a connection may carry current during the normal operation of a device.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Such devices include surge suppression, electromagnetic-compatibility filters, some types of antennas, and various measurement instruments.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Generally the protective earth system is also used as a functional earth, though this requires care.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Distribution power systems may be solidly grounded, with one circuit conductor directly connected to an earth grounding electrode system.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Alternatively, some amount of electrical impedance may be connected between the distribution system and ground, to limit the current that can flow to earth.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] The impedance may be a resistor, or an inductor (coil).
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] In a high-impedance grounded system, the fault current is limited to a few amperes (exact values depend on the voltage class of the system); a low-impedance grounded system will permit several hundred amperes to flow on a fault.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] A large solidly grounded distribution system may have tens of thousands of amperes of ground fault current.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] In a polyphase AC system, the instantaneous vector sum of the phases is zero.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] This neutral point is commonly used to refer the phase voltages to earth ground instead of connecting one of the phase conductors to earth.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Any Δ-Y (delta-wye) connected transformer may be used for the purpose.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] A nine winding transformer (a "zig zag" transformer) may be used to balance the phase currents of a delta connected source with an unbalanced load.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Low-resistance grounding systems use a neutral grounding resistor (NGR) to limit the fault current to 25 A or greater.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Low resistance grounding systems will have a time rating (say, 10 seconds) that indicates how long the resistor can carry the fault current before overheating.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] A ground fault protection relay must trip the breaker to protect the circuit before overheating of the resistor occurs.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] High-resistance grounding (HRG) systems use an NGR to limit the fault current to 25 A or less.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] They have a continuous rating, and are designed to operate with a single-ground fault.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] This means that the system will not immediately trip on the first ground fault.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] If a second ground fault occurs, a ground fault protection relay must trip the breaker to protect the circuit.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] On an HRG system, a sensing resistor is used to continuously monitor system continuity.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] If an open-circuit is detected (e.g., due to a broken weld on the NGR), the monitoring device will sense voltage through the sensing resistor and trip the breaker.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Without a sensing resistor, the system could continue to operate without ground protection (since an open circuit condition would mask the ground fault) and transient overvoltages could occur.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Where the danger of electric shock is high, special ungrounded power systems may be used to minimize possible leakage current to ground.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Examples of such installations include patient care areas in hospitals, where medical equipment is directly connected to a patient and must not permit any power-line current to pass into the patient's body.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Medical systems include monitoring devices to warn of any increase of leakage current.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] On wet construction sites or in shipyards, isolation transformers may be provided so that a fault in a power tool or its cable does not expose users to shock hazard.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Circuits used to feed sensitive audio/video production equipment or measurement instruments may be fed from an isolated ungrounded technical power system to limit the injection of noise from the power system.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] In single-wire earth return (SWER) AC electrical distribution systems, costs are saved by using just a single high voltage conductor for the power grid, while routing the AC return current through the earth.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] This system is mostly used in rural areas where large earth currents will not otherwise cause hazards.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Some high-voltage direct-current (HVDC) power transmission systems use the ground as second conductor.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] This is especially common in schemes with submarine cables, as sea water is a good conductor.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Buried grounding electrodes are used to make the connection to the earth.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] The site of these electrodes must be chosen carefully to prevent electrochemical corrosion on underground structures.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] A particular concern in design of electrical substations is earth potential rise.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] When very large fault currents are injected into the earth, the area around the point of injection may rise to a high potential with respect to points distant from it.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] This is due to the limited finite conductivity of the layers of soil in the earth of the substation.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] The gradient of the voltage (the change in voltage across the distance to the injection point) may be so high that two points on the ground may be at significantly different potentials.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] This gradient creates a hazard to anyone standing on the earth in an area of the electrical substation that is insufficiently insulated from ground.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Pipes, rails, or communication wires entering a substation may see different ground potentials inside and outside the substation, creating a dangerous touch voltage for unsuspecting persons who might touch those pipes, rails, or wires.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] This problem is alleviated by creating a low-impedance equipotential bonding plane installed in accordance with IEEE 80, within the substation.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] This plane eliminates voltage gradients and ensures that any fault is cleared within three voltage cycles.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Lightning protection systems are designed to mitigate the effects of lightning through connection to extensive grounding systems that provide a large surface area connection to earth.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] The large area is required to dissipate the high current of a lightning strike without damaging the system conductors by excess heat.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Since lightning strikes are pulses of energy with very high frequency components, grounding systems for lightning protection tend to use short straight runs of conductors to reduce the self-inductance and skin effect.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] In the vicinity of electrostatic sensitive devices, a ground mat is used to ground static electricity generated by people and moving equipment.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] There are two types used in static control: Static Dissipative Mats, and Conductive Mats.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] A static dissipative mat that rests on a conductive surface (commonly the case in military facilities) are typically made of three layers (3-ply) with static dissipative vinyl layers surrounding a conductive substrate which is electrically attached to ground.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] For commercial uses, static dissipative rubber mats are traditionally used that are made of two layers (2-ply) with a tough solder resistant top static dissipative layer that makes them last longer than the vinyl mats, and a conductive rubber bottom.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Conductive mats are made of carbon and used only on floors for the purpose of drawing static electricity to ground as quickly as possible.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Normally conductive mats are made with cushioning for standing and are referred to as "anti-fatigue" mats.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] For a static dissipative mat to be reliably grounded it must be attached to a path to ground.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Normally, both the mat and the wrist strap are connected to ground by using a common point ground system (CPGS).
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] In computer repair shops and electronics manufacturing, workers must be grounded before working on devices sensitive to voltages capable of being generated by humans.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] For that reason static dissipative mats can be and are also used on production assembly floors as "floor runner" along the assembly line to draw static generated by people walking up and down.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Signal grounds serve as return paths for signals and power (at extra-low voltages, less than about 50 V) within equipment, and on the signal interconnections between equipment.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Many electronic designs feature a single return that acts as a reference for all signals.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Power and signal grounds often get connected, usually through the metal case of the equipment.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Designers of printed circuit boards must take care in the layout of electronic systems so that high-power or rapidly switching currents in one part of a system do not inject noise into low-level sensitive parts of a system due to some common impedance in the grounding traces of the layout.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Voltage is defined as the difference of electric potentials between points in an electric field.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] A voltmeter is used to measure the potential difference between some point and a convenient, but otherwise arbitrary reference point.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] This common reference point is denoted "ground" and is designated as having a nominal zero potential.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Signals are defined with respect to signal ground, which may be connected to a power ground.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] A system where the system ground is not connected to another circuit or to earth (in which there may still be AC coupling between those circuits) is often referred to as a floating ground, and may correspond to Class 0 or Class II appliances.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Some devices require a connection to the mass of earth to function correctly, as distinct from any purely protective role.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Because of this separation, a purely functional ground should not normally be relied upon to perform a protective function.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] To avoid accidents, such functional grounds are normally wired in white, cream or pink cable, and not green or green/yellow.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] In television stations, recording studios, and other installations where signal quality is critical, a special signal ground known as a "technical ground" (or "technical earth", "special earth", and "audio earth") is often installed, to prevent ground loops.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] This is basically the same thing as an AC power ground, but no general appliance ground wires are allowed any connection to it, as they may carry electrical interference.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] For example, only audio equipment is connected to the technical ground in a recording studio.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] In most cases, the studio's metal equipment racks are all joined with heavy copper cables (or flattened copper tubing or busbars) and similar connections are made to the technical ground.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Great care is taken that no general chassis grounded appliances are placed on the racks, as a single AC ground connection to the technical ground will destroy its effectiveness.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] For particularly demanding applications, the main technical ground may consist of a heavy copper pipe, if necessary fitted by drilling through several concrete floors, such that all technical grounds may be connected by the shortest possible path to a grounding rod in the basement.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Long-distance electromagnetic telegraph systems from 1820 onwards used two or more wires to carry the signal and return currents.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] It was discovered by German scientist C.A. von Steinheil in 1836–1837, that the ground could be used as the return path to complete the circuit, making the return wire unnecessary.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Steinheil was not the first to do this, but he was not aware of earlier experimental work, and he was the first to do it on an in-service telegraph, thus making the principle known to telegraph engineers generally.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] However, there were problems with this system, exemplified by the transcontinental telegraph line constructed in 1861 by the Western Union Company between St.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Joseph, Missouri, and Sacramento, California.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] During dry weather, the ground connection often developed a high resistance, requiring water to be poured on the ground rod to enable the telegraph to work or phones to ring.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Certain types of radio antennas (or their feedlines) require a connection to ground that functions adequately at radio frequencies.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] This type of ground is called a *radio frequency ground*.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] A radio frequency ground that establishes a low-resistance return path for the electrical field produced by the antenna during the process of creating radiated waves.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Although some of these grounds might be combined, and should be connected at exactly one point, only the last type of ground is covered in this section.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Lightning safety grounding (1) is covered in the following section, not here.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] The electrical safety ground (2) was discussed in previous sections and is unsuitable for radio purposes, although required for the power supply.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] The radio frequency ground (3) is the topic of this section.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Since the radio frequencies of the current in antennas are far higher than the 50 or 60 Hz frequency of the power line, radio grounding systems use different principles than AC power grounding.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] The "protective earth" (PE) safety ground wires in AC utility building wiring were not designed for, and cannot be used as an adequate substitute for an RF ground.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] The long utility ground wires have high impedance at certain frequencies.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] In the case of a transmitter, the RF current flowing through the ground wires can radiate radio frequency interference and induce hazardous voltages on grounded metal parts of other appliances, so separate ground systems are used.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Monopole antennas operating at lower frequencies, below 20 MHz, use the surface of the Earth as a part of the antenna, as a conductive plane to reflect the radio waves and provide a return path for electric fields extending from the antenna.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Types of earth-grounded monopoles include the mast radiator used by AM radio stations, the 'T' and inverted 'L' antenna, and umbrella antenna.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] The feedline from the transmitter is connected between the antenna and ground, so it requires a grounding (earthing) system under the antenna to make contact with the soil to collect the return current.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] The ground system also functions as a capacitor plate, to receive the displacement current from the antenna and return it to the ground side of the transmitter's feedline, so it is preferably located directly under the antenna.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] In receivers and low efficiency / low power transmitters, the ground connection can be as simple as one or several metal rods or stakes driven into the soil, or an electrical connection to a building's metal water piping which extends into the earth.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] However, in transmitting antennas the ground system carries the full output current of the transmitter, so the resistance of an inadequate ground contact can be a major loss of transmitter power.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Medium to high power transmitters usually have an extensive ground system consisting of bare copper cables buried in the earth under the antenna, to lower resistance.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] The transmitter power lost in the ground resistance, and so the efficiency of the antenna, depends on the soil conductivity.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] This varies widely; marshy ground or ponds, particularly salt water, provide the lowest resistance ground, while dry rocky or sandy soil are the highest.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] The power loss per square meter in the ground is proportional to the square of the transmitter current density flowing in the earth.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] A standard ground system widely used for mast radiator broadcasting antennas operating in the MF and LF bands consists of 120 equally-spaced, buried, radial ground wires extending out one quarter of a wavelength ( $\ {\tfrac {1}{4}}\lambda \$ , or 90 electrical degrees) from the antenna base.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] AWG 8 to AWG 10 soft-drawn copper wire is typically used, buried 4–10 in (100–250 mm) deep.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] For AM broadcast band antennas this requires a circular land area extending from the mast 47–136 meters (154–446 ft).
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] This is usually planted with grass, which is kept mowed short, as tall grass can increase power loss in certain circumstances.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] If the land area available is too limited for such long radials, they can in many cases be adequately replaced by a greater number of shorter radials, or a smaller number of longer radials.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] In transmitting antennas a second cause of power wastage is dielectric power losses of the electric field (displacement current) of the antenna passing through the earth to reach the ground wires.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] For antennas near a half-wavelength high (180 electrical degrees) the antenna has a voltage maximum (antinode) near its base, which results in strong electric fields in the earth above the ground wires near the mast where the displacement current enters the ground.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] To reduce this loss these antennas often use a conductive copper ground screen under the antenna connected to the buried ground wires, either lying on the ground or elevated a few feet, to shield the ground from the electric field.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] In a few cases where rocky or sandy soil has too high a resistance for a buried ground, a counterpoise is used.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] This is a radial network of wires similar to that in a buried ground system, but lying on the surface or suspended a few feet above the ground.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] It acts as a capacitor plate, capacitively coupling the feedline to conductive layers of the soil.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] At lower frequencies the resistance of the ground system is a more critical factor because of the small radiation resistance of the antenna.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] In the LF and VLF bands, construction height limitations require that electrically short antennas be used, shorter than the fundamental resonant length of one quarter of a wavelength ( $\ {\tfrac {1}{4}}\lambda \$ ).
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] A quarter wave monopole has a radiation resistance of around 25~36 ohms, but below $\ {\tfrac {1}{4}}\lambda \$ the resistance decreases with the square of the ratio of height to wavelength.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] The power fed to an antenna is split between the radiation resistance, which represents power emitted as radio waves, the desired function of the antenna, and the ohmic resistance of the ground system, which results in power wasted as heat.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] As the wavelength gets longer in relation to antenna height, the radiation resistance of the antenna decreases so the ground resistance constitutes a larger proportion of the input resistance of the antenna and consumes more of the transmitter power.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Antennas in the VLF band often have a resistance of less than 1 ohm, and even with extremely low resistance ground systems 50% to 90% of the transmitter power may be wasted in the ground system.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Isolation is a mechanism that defeats grounding.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] It is frequently used with low-power consumer devices, and when engineers, hobbyists, or repairmen are working on circuits that would normally be operated using the power line voltage.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Isolation can be accomplished by simply placing a "1:1 wire ratio" transformer with an equal number of turns between the device and the regular power service, but applies to any type of transformer using two or more coils electrically insulated from each other.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] For an isolated device, touching a single powered conductor does not cause a severe shock, because there is no path back to the other conductor through the ground.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] However, shocks and electrocution may still occur if both poles of the transformer are contacted by bare skin.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Previously it was suggested that repairmen "work with one hand behind their back" to avoid touching two parts of the device under test at the same time, thereby preventing a current from crossing through the chest and interrupting cardiac rhythms or causing cardiac arrest.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Generally every AC power line transformer acts as an isolation transformer, and every step up or down has the potential to form an isolated circuit.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] However, this isolation would prevent failed devices from blowing fuses when shorted to their ground conductor.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] The isolation that could be created by each transformer is defeated by always having one leg of the transformers grounded, on both sides of the input and output transformer coils.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Power lines also typically ground one specific wire at every pole, to ensure current equalization from pole to pole if a short to ground is occurring.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Modern appliances however often include power entry modules which are designed with deliberate capacitive coupling between the AC power lines and chassis, to suppress electromagnetic interference.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] This results in a significant leakage current from the power lines to ground.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] If the ground is disconnected by a cheater plug or by accident, the resulting leakage current can cause mild shocks, even without any fault in the equipment.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Even small leakage currents are a significant concern in medical settings, as the accidental disconnection of ground can introduce these currents into sensitive parts of the human body.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] As a result, medical power supplies are designed to have low capacitance.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Class II appliances and power supplies (such as cell phone chargers) do not provide any ground connection, and are designed to isolate the output from input.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-electricity] Safety is ensured by double-insulation, so that two failures of insulation are required to cause a shock.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] In an electrical system, a **ground loop** or **earth loop** occurs when two points of a circuit are intended to have the same ground reference potential but instead have a different potential between them.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] This is typically caused when enough current is flowing in the connection between the two ground points to produce a voltage drop and cause the two points to be at different potentials.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] Current may be produced in a ground loop by electromagnetic induction.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] Ground loops are a major cause of noise, hum, and interference in audio, video, and computer systems.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] Wiring practices that protect against ground loops include ensuring that all vulnerable signal circuits are referenced to one point as ground.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] The use of differential signaling can provide rejection of ground-induced interference.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] The removal of ground connections to equipment in an effort to eliminate ground loops will also eliminate the protection the safety ground connection is intended to provide.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] A ground loop is caused by the interconnection of electrical devices that results in multiple paths to ground, thereby forming closed conductive loops through the ground connections.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] A common example is two electrical devices, each connected to a mains power outlet by a three-conductor cable and plug containing a protective ground conductor for safety.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] When signal cables are connected between both devices, the shield of the signal cable is typically connected to the grounded chassis of both devices.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] This forms a closed loop through the ground conductors of the power cords, which are connected through the building wiring.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] In the vicinity of electric power wiring, there will always be stray magnetic fields, particularly from utility lines oscillating at line frequency (50 or 60 hertz).
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] These ambient magnetic fields passing through the ground loop will induce a current in the loop by electromagnetic induction.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] The ground loop acts as a single-turn secondary winding of a transformer, the primary being the summation of all current-carrying conductors nearby.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] The amount of current induced will depend on the magnitude and proximity of nearby currents.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] The presence of high-power equipment, such as industrial motors or transformers can increase the interference.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] Since the conductors comprising the ground loop usually have very low resistance, often below one ohm, even weak magnetic fields can induce significant currents.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] Since the ground conductor of the signal cable linking the two devices is part of the signal path of the cable, the alternating ground current flowing through the cable can introduce electrical interference in the signal.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] The induced alternating current flowing through the resistance of the cable ground conductor will cause a small AC voltage drop across the cable ground.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] This is added to the signal applied to the input of the next stage.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] In audio equipment, the line frequency interference may be heard as a hum in the speakers.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] In a video system it may cause distortion or synchronization problems.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] In computer data connections, it can cause slowdowns or failures of data transfer.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] Ground loops can also exist within the internal circuits of electronic equipment, as design flaws.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] The addition of signal interconnection cables to a system where equipment enclosures are already required to be bonded to ground can create ground loops.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] Proper design of such a system will satisfy both safety grounding requirements and signal integrity.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] For this reason, in some large professional installations such as recording studios, it is sometimes the practice to provide two completely separate ground connections to equipment bays.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] One is the normal safety ground that connects to exposed metalwork, the other is a technical ground for cable screens and the like.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] The circuit diagram illustrates a simple ground loop.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] Circuit 1 (left) and circuit 2 (right) share a common path to ground of resistance $\scriptstyle R_{G}$ .
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] Ideally, this ground conductor would have no resistance ( $\scriptstyle R_{G}=0$ ), yielding no voltage drop across it ( $\scriptstyle V_{G}=0$ ), keeping the connection point between the circuits at a constant ground potential.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] In that case, the output of circuit 2 is simply $\scriptstyle V_{\text{out}}=V_{2}$ .
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] However, if this ground conductor has some resistance ( $\scriptstyle R_{G}>0$ ), then it forms a voltage divider with $\scriptstyle R_{1}$ .
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] As a result, if a current ( $\scriptstyle I_{1}$ ) is flowing through $\scriptstyle R_{G}$ from circuit 1, then a voltage drop across $\scriptstyle R_{G}$ of $\scriptstyle V_{G}\;=\;I_{1}R_{G}$ occurs, causing the shared ground connection to no longer be at the actual ground potential.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] Thus, the two circuits are no longer isolated, and circuit 1 can introduce interference into the output of circuit 2.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] If circuit 2 is an audio system and circuit 1 has large AC currents flowing in it, the interference may be heard as a 50 or 60 Hz hum in the speakers.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] Also, both circuits have voltage $\scriptstyle V_{G}$ on their grounded parts that may be exposed to contact, possibly presenting a shock hazard.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] This is true even if circuit 2 is turned off.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] Although ground loops occur most often in the ground conductors of electrical equipment, similar loops can occur wherever two or more circuits share a common current path.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] If enough current flows, similar problems occur in these conditions.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] A common type of ground loop is due to faulty interconnections between electronic components, such as laboratory or recording studio equipment, or home component audio, video, and computer systems.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] This can create inadvertent closed loops in the ground wiring circuit, which can allow stray line frequency AC current to be induced and flow through the ground conductors of signal cables.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] The voltage drops in the ground system caused by these currents are added to the signal path, introducing noise and hum into the output.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] The loops can include the building's utility wiring ground system when more than one component is grounded through the protective earth (third wire) in their power cords.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] The symptoms of a ground loop, ground noise and hum in electrical equipment are caused by current flowing in the ground or *shield* conductor of a cable.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] 1 shows a signal cable *S* linking two electronic components, including the typical line driver and receiver amplifiers *(triangles)*.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] The cable has a ground or shield conductor which is connected to the chassis ground of each component.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] The driver amplifier in component 1 *(left)* applies signal *V*1 between the signal and ground conductors of the cable.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] At the destination end *(right)*, the signal and ground conductors are connected to a differential amplifier.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] If *I* is an AC current, this can result in noise added to the signal path in component 2.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] The diagrams in this section show a typical ground loop caused by a signal cable *S* connecting two grounded electronic components *C1* and *C2*.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] The loop consists of the signal cable's ground conductor, which is connected through the components' metal chassis to the ground wires *P* in their power cords, which are plugged into outlet grounds that are connected through the building's utility ground wire system *G*.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] The solution to ground loop noise is to break the ground loop or otherwise prevent the current from flowing.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] A hazardous technique sometimes used by amateurs is to break the *third wire* ground conductor *P* in one of the component's power cords, by removing the ground pin on the plug, or using a cheater plug.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] This creates an electric shock hazard by leaving one of the components ungrounded.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] A more comprehensive solution is to use equipment that employs differential signaling.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] Ground noise can only get into the signal path in single-ended signaling, in which the ground or shield conductor serves as one side of the signal path.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] When the signal is sent as a differential signal along a pair of wires, neither of which are connected to ground, any noise from the ground system induced in the signal lines is a common-mode signal, identical in both wires.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] Since the line receiver at the destination end only responds to differential signals, a difference in voltage between the two lines, the common-mode noise is canceled out.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] Thus these systems are very immune to electrical noise, including ground noise.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] Professional and scientific equipment often uses differential signaling with balanced lines.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] So, when a current is induced in the loop, there will be a voltage drop along the signal ground return.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] This is directly additive to the wanted signal and will result in objectionable hum.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] For instance, if a current I of 1 mA at the local power frequency is induced in the ground loop, and the resistance R of the screen of the signal cable is 100 mΩ, the voltage drop will be $V=I\cdot R$ = 100 μV.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] This is a significant fraction of the output voltage of a moving coil pickup cartridge, and imposes an objectionable hum on the cartridge output.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] Attempting to cure these problems by removing the protective ground conductor creates a shock hazard.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] Solving hum problems must be done in the signal interconnections, and this is done in two main ways, which may be combined.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] Isolation is the quickest, quietest and most foolproof method of resolving hum problems.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] The signal is isolated by a small transformer, such that the source and destination equipment each retain their own protective ground connections, but there is no through connection from one to the other in the signal path.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] By transformer isolating all unbalanced connections, the unbalanced connections are converted to balanced connections.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] In analog applications such as audio, the physical limitations of the transformers cause some signal degradation, by limiting bandwidth and adding some distortion.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] Balanced connections see the spurious noise due to ground loop current as common-mode interference while the signal is differential, enabling them to be separated at the destination by circuits having a high common-mode rejection ratio.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] This rejection can be accomplished with transformers or semiconductor output drivers and line receivers.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] With the increasing trend towards digital processing and transmission of audio signals, the full range of isolation by small pulse transformers, optocouplers or fiber optics become more useful.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] Standard protocols such as S/PDIF, AES3 or TOSLINK are available in relatively inexpensive equipment and allow full isolation, so ground loops need not arise, especially when connecting between audio systems and computers.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] In instrumentation systems, the use of differential inputs with high common-mode rejection ratio, to minimize the effects of induced AC signals on the parameter to be measured, is widespread.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] It may also be possible to introduce narrow notch filters at the power frequency and its lower harmonics; however, this can not be done in audio systems due to the objectionable audible effects on the wanted signal.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] In analog video, mains hum can be seen as hum bars (bands of slightly different brightness) scrolling vertically up the screen.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] These are frequently seen with video projectors where the display device has its case grounded via a 3-prong plug, and the other components have a floating ground connected to the CATV coax.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] In this situation the video cable is grounded at the projector end to the home electrical system, and at the other end to the cable TV's ground, inducing a current through the cable which distorts the picture.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] The problem is best solved with an isolation transformer in the CATV RF feed, a feature included in some CATV box designs.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] Ground loop issues with television coaxial cable can affect any connected audio device such as a receiver.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] In digital systems, which commonly transmit data serially (RS-232, RS-485, USB, FireWire, DVI, HDMI etc.) the signal voltage is often much larger than induced power frequency AC on the connecting cable screens.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] Of those protocols listed, only RS-232 is single-ended with ground return, but it is a large signal, typically + and - 12V, all the others being differential.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] Differential signaling must use a balanced line to ensure that the signal does not radiate and that induced noise from a ground loop is a common-mode signal and can be removed at the differential receiver.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] Many data communications systems such as Ethernet 10BASE-T, 100BASE-TX and 1000BASE-T, use DC-balanced encoding such as Manchester code.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] The ground loop(s) which would occur in most installations are avoided by using signal-isolating transformers.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] Other systems break the ground loop at data frequencies by fitting small ferrite beads around the connecting cables near each end or just inside the equipment boundary.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] These form a common-mode choke which inhibits unbalanced current flow, without affecting the differential signal.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] Coaxial cables used at radio frequencies may be wound several times through a ferrite bead to add a useful amount of common-mode inductance.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] This limits the flow of unwanted high-frequency common-mode current along the cable shield.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] Where no power need be transmitted, only digital data, the use of fiber optics can remove many ground loop problems, and sometimes safety problems too.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] Optical isolators or optocouplers are frequently used to provide ground loop isolation, and often safety isolation and can help prevent fault propagation.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] Generally, the analog and digital parts of the circuit are in separate areas of the PCB, with their own ground planes to obtain the necessary low inductance grounding and avoid ground bounce.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] These are tied together at a carefully chosen star point.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] Where analog-to-digital converters (ADCs) are in use, the star point may have to be at or very close to the ground terminals of the ADC(s).
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] Phase lock loop circuits are particularly vulnerable because the VCO loop filter circuit is working with sub-microvolt signals when the loop is locked, and any disturbance will cause frequency jitter and possible loss of lock.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] Grounding and the potential for ground loops are also important considerations in circuit design.
[src:grounding-shielding/ground-loop-electricity] In many circuits, large currents may exist through the ground plane, leading to voltage differences of the ground reference in different parts of the circuit, which can lead to hum and other problems.
